11. July, 1642. The King ſends to the Parlament to cauſe the Town of Hull to be delivered unto him, and deſires to have their anſwer by the 15 of that month, and as then had uſed no force againſt it: But the morrow Ibid. 452. after before that meſſage could come unto them they reſolve upon the Queſtion: That Ibid. 457. an Army ſhall be forthwith raiſed for the defence of the Kings perſon and both houſes of Parlament;
Ibid. 457.
and thoſe who have obeyed their Orders and Commands; in preſerving the true Religion, the Laws, Liberties, and the Peace of the Kingdom; and that they would live and dye with the Earl of Eſſex, whom they nominate Generall in that cauſe.
